<h2>Academic work</h2>
<p align="justify">Since October 2005 I have been studying for a doctorate in the department of <a href="http://www.atm.ox.ac.uk">Atmospheric, Oceanic and Planetary Physics</a> at <a href="http://www.trinity.ox.ac.uk">Trinity College, University of Oxford</a> in the Earth Observation Data Group <a href="http://www.atm.ox.ac.uk/group/eodg/index.html">(EODG)</a>. My area of research is aerosol retrievals from AATSR (a radiometer aboard the European Space Agency's <a href="http://envisat.esa.int/instruments/aatsr/">Envisat</a>), where I have been involved in the development and application of a dual-view optimal estimation retrieval algorithm. In the future we hope to use the algorithm to focus on the transport of Saharan dust across the Atlantic, and obtain estimates for mass flux and dust destinations.</p>

<p align="justify">My work is funded by <a href="http://www.nerc.ac.uk/">NERC</a> and supervised by Don Grainger here at AOPP and Chris Mutlow at the <a href="http://www.sstd.rl.ac.uk/">Rutherford Appleton Laboratory</a>. I also work closely with several postdocs in the group, namely <a href="http://www.atm.ox.ac.uk/group/eodg/eodg_people.html">Gareth Thomas (my postdoctoral adviser), Elisa Carboni and Elies Campmany</a>.</p>

<h2>Academic history</h2>
<p align="justify">In 2005 I graduated from the <a href="http://www.york.ac.uk/depts/chem/">Department of Chemistry, University of York</a> with an MChem. My Masters project was supervised by <a href="http://www.york.ac.uk/depts/chem/staff/ss.html">Dr. Seishi Shimizu</a>, and involved Monte Carlo simulations of insertion of hydrophobic particles into bulk water, to probe the thermodynamics of the process. While at York I also did some research under David Smith into anion binding by catechol derivatives, which was funded by the Nuffield Foundation.</p>

